The paper deals with the role of shared randomness in communication complexity, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several sub-fields of computer science. The use of shared randomness is closely related to information theory (cs.IT) and communication complexity (cs.CC), as well as data structures (cs.DS) and cryptography (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper introduces a new measure called collision complexity, which is a concept that is relevant to the study of discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
